{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01ScsBo8LAZPXEM3nhMQKc1F","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a clear picture of the raw JSON format. The `full.log` contains entries like:\n\n```\n[timestamp] [llm] {\"type\":\"assistant\",\"message\":{\"model\":\"...\",\"content\":[{\"type\":\"text\",\"text\":\"...\"},{\"type\":\"tool_use\",\"id\":\"...\",\"name\":\"Read\",\"input\":{...}},...]},...}\n[timestamp] [llm] {\"type\":\"user\",\"message\":{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":[{\"tool_use_id\":\"...\",\"type\":\"tool_result\",\"content\":\"...\"}]},...}\n[timestamp] [llm] {\"type\":\"system\",\"subtype\":\"init\",...}\n\n\n```\n\nI'm seeing the full range of event types in the stream—rate limit events, final results, step transitions between started and completed states, and script entries. The main message types are system initialization events, assistant responses with thinking blocks and tool calls, and user messages with tool results.\n\nFor the human-readable log output, I need to filter and display only the relevant events: extract text content from assistant messages, show tool names and input summaries for tool_use blocks, optionally include tool results, display final cost and timing information, and pass through status and script entries as-is while skipping system init, rate limits, and thinking blocks.\n\nI'm planning to create a new package or extend the existing logstream module that parses the raw JSON content from llm-type log entries and formats them into a readable output.\n\nLooking at the actual data flow, the llm log lines contain raw Claude Code streaming JSON that I need to parse and extract meaningful content from. I'll add a FormatLLMContent function that takes the raw JSON string and returns a human-readable summary, then apply this formatting in the SSE handler for both live and archived logs. I need to handle the formatting at the web handler level where LogLine objects are created for the SSE stream, so it applies to both live and archived runs while keeping the raw JSON in storage for debugging purposes. For the live broadcast path, I can apply the same formatting when publishing to the log stream. Applying formatting in the live stream path by checking the message type and transforming the content before marshaling it to JSON. I'm also considering whether to filter out certain message types entirely—like system initialization messages that are just noise, or rate limit events unless they're errors.\n\nFor messages with assistant thinking, I'll skip those since they're internal reasoning, but show actual text responses and tool calls with a brief summary. The formatting function will parse the JSON content and extract readable information, returning an empty string for messages that should be skipped so the handler can filter them out.\n\nWriting the format function... Writing the result formatter... Writing tool formatting logic... Finishing the switch statement for different action types, then I need to set up the format module and apply it to the web handler. I should also check the step output handler to see if those files need the same formatting treatment. I'm creating a helper function to format log lines consistently, checking if they're LLM type and applying the formatting logic. Since a single JSON entry might expand into multiple human-readable lines, I'll join them with newlines and let the frontend handle the display. Now I need to integrate this into both the live SSE stream and the archived log parsing paths. I'm looking at how the agent adapter extracts text from the stream JSON output, specifically checking what gets written to the log stream and whether I need to handle any pre-processing of the log content.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":36128,"cache_read_input_tokens":38236,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"