{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01LNojtVaBB5zh4Dr3pCq9nD","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the full picture. The key insight is:\n\n1. **In the full.log** (which is what the web UI displays for completed runs), the `[llm]` entries contain the raw Claude Code streaming JSON. Each line is the full JSON event from Claude Code's `--output-format stream-json`.\n\n2. **For live runs**, the agent adapter (`prompt.go`) uses `extractStreamText()` to extract only the text content from `content_block_delta` events, and streams those extracted text lines via `StatusWriter.Log()`. The StatusWriter emits a `protocol.StatusMessage{Type: \"log\", Message: textLine}` which the gRPC server publishes as `LogLine{Type: \"llm\", Content: textLine}`.\n\n\n3. **For completed runs**, the full.log file is written by `logstream.Writer` inside the container and contains the raw JSON events exactly as they came from Claude Code, which is why the web UI shows unreadable JSON instead of the extracted text that live runs display.\n\n4. The agent adapter streams extracted text lines through `StatusWriter.Log()`, which creates status messages that go to the gRPC server, but I need to trace where the full.log is actually getting populated from — it seems like the raw Claude Code JSON output is being written directly to the log file rather than the extracted text lines. is scanned line by line\n5. `extractStreamText()` extracts text from `content_block_delta` events\n6. Extracted text is sent via `StatusWriter.Log()` to stdout (container stdout)\n7. The raw Claude output is also written to `{step}.log` file (line 123: `os.WriteFile(filepath.Join(outputDir, step.Name+\".log\"), lastStdout, 0644)`)\n\nBut also, the `rawBuf` contains ALL raw Claude output lines. And `lastStdout` is `rawBuf.Bytes()`. So the step output file (`implement.log`) contains the raw JSON.\n\nNow, what about `full.log`? Looking at the logstream.Writer usage... The agent writes to it via `logstream.Writer.Log()`. Let me check who creates and uses the logstream.Writer inside the container.\n\nNow I need to look at the cloche-agent entrypoint to understand how the logstream.Writer is initialized and what it's writing to.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":8796,"cache_read_input_tokens":74364,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":8796},"output_tokens":10,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"65a45440-8ea2-48ce-9346-c9049e4bd586","uuid":"f9471fdb-bbb7-45d3-9003-f3355a562eb9"}
